communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Orange Team JCS
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am looking for files on the groups planning unconventional and psychological warfare in the Joint Strategic Planning Group during the cold war.

I would like any files from a keyword on JSPG file of an "Orange Team", "Brown Team", "strategic deception", or "special plans", in the years 1946-1973. My understanding is that Orange Team handled strategic deception planning and Brown Team handled unconventional warfare.

I received the followsing guidance from OSD/JS:
" The Office of Secretary of Defense/Joint Staff (OSD/JS) FOIA office received your request on September 4, 2024, and assigned it FOIA case number 24-F-3016. We ask that you use this number when referring to your request. Please note that your request was misdirected to this office for processing, as this FOIA office only processes requests for the OSD/JS. Although it is possible that the records you have requested were once maintained by OSD/JS, due to the age of the records, if they still exist, they would be maintained at the National Archives and Records Administration (NARA), which operates its own FOIA program. NARA is the independent Federal agency that helps to preserve and care for records of historical value. For your convenience, contact information for the NARA FOIA office is provided below: The National Archives at College Park Office of General Counsel 8601 Adelphi Road NGC, Room 3110 College Park, MD 20740-6001 foia@nara.gov"


The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brian Mills
